{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509152"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:14:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:14:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11390"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11390"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.18,0.46,0.27,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106838"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4035"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11390"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89324"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1966"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37962"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106838"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a two-month history of intermittent double vision following a concussive blow to the side of his head sustained during a tackle in a football game. He only sees a double picture when he looks downwards or upwards and finds walking downstairs awkward. When he tilts his head to one side, normal vision is restored. His family have also noticed a recent personality change. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His monocular vision is normal and the diplopia does not occur when either eye is covered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebrospinal fluid leak","Frontal lobe meningioma","Trauma","Subdural haematoma","Multiple sclerosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has binocular diplopia, as evidenced by the diplopia resolving when one eye is covered. The vertical diplopia that worsens on downgaze and improves with compensatory head tilt is characteristic of a trochlear nerve palsy. The trochlear nerve is the longest and thinnest cranial nerve, exiting the brainstem dorsally to innervate the contralateral superior oblique muscle, making it particularly vulnerable to injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrauma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause in this young patient with a clear history of head injury. The anatomy of the trochlear nerve makes it susceptible to traumatic injury, and the timeline correlates with the football injury. The personality change may be related to concurrent mild traumatic brain injury from the same incident.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebrospinal fluid leak\u003C/strong\u003E can occur after head trauma but typically presents with clear fluid draining from the nose or ears, headaches, and altered sense of taste. It would not directly cause an isolated trochlear nerve palsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal lobe meningioma\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the personality change through mass effect on frontal cortex, but would typically present with additional symptoms including headaches and nausea. It is unlikely to cause an isolated trochlear nerve palsy and would be unusual in this age group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esubdural haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E can occur following head trauma and may cause personality changes through increased intracranial pressure or direct cortical compression. However, it typically presents with headache, confusion, and progressive neurological deterioration rather than an isolated trochlear nerve palsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause diplopia in young adults, but typically presents with other neurological symptoms such as sensory disturbances, weakness, or optic neuritis in a relapsing-remitting pattern. The clear temporal relationship with trauma makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Diplopia can be monocular or binocular, with binocular diplopia often due to disorders of extraocular muscles, cranial nerves, or the neuromuscular junction.","Trochlear nerve palsy typically presents with vertical diplopia worse on downgaze that improves with compensatory head tilt.","Trauma is a common cause of trochlear nerve palsy in young patients, as the trochlear nerve is the longest and thinnest cranial nerve making it vulnerable to injury."],"references":["Morillon P, Bremner F. Trochlear nerve palsy. Br J Hosp Med. 2017;78(3):C38-C40. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28277775/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89324"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11390"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89324"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-23T16:23:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-23T16:26:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4035"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106838"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":